\begin_layout Standard
Exactly solvable chaotic dynamical systems are interesting because they
 provide insight into the behaviour of chaotic dynamical systems 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

in the large
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The simplest exactly solvable model of deterministic chaos is the iterated
 Bernoulli map
\begin_inset LatexCommand cite
key "Dri99"

\end_inset

.
 It is a map of the unit interval onto itself, given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
b(x)=2x\mbox{ mod }1\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Picking some 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

random
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 irrational 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and then iterating this map, one sees 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{n}(x)$
\end_inset

 bounce all over the unit interval: the map is ergodic.
 One may compute correlation functions for it, and other statistical measures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One method for studying a chaotic map is in terms of its Frobenius-Perron
 or transfer operator.
 The utility of the transfer operator can be introduced by an appeal to
 physics, and the statistical mechanics of continuum systems.
 The argument goes as follows: while iterated maps have a point dynamics
 that bounces all over the place, in nature, physical observables are smooth.
 Therefore, one should study the dynamics of a smooth distribution of particles
 under the action of chaotic operators.
 The transfer operator gives exactly such an opportunity.
 It is defined as a certain map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}:\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is some collection of functions on the unit interval.
 For example one may take 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}=\mathcal{P}(x)$
\end_inset

 the set of polynomials in one variable, or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}=L^{2}([0,1])$
\end_inset

 the set of square-integral functions on the unit interval.
 Given some iterated function (for example, 
\begin_inset Formula $b(x)$
\end_inset

), it is defined as the map 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}f=g\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 such that, on a pointwise basis, one has 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g(x)=\sum_{y\in b^{-1}(x)}\;\frac{f(y)}{b^{\prime}(y)}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{\prime}(y)$
\end_inset

 is the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 When the pre-image 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{-1}(x)$
\end_inset

 is not a countable collection of points, the sum may be replaced by an
 integral.
 The transfer operator can be defined with varying degrees of sophistication
 and rigor, and can be found in many places in the literature; simple, workable
 definitions can be found in 
\begin_inset LatexCommand cite
key "Dri99,Ve-T04"

\end_inset

.
 In short, while iterating a function such as 
\begin_inset Formula $b(x)$
\end_inset

 gives the time evolution of a point, iterating the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 gives the time evolution of a smooth distribution.
 A general feature that is physically appealing is that the transfer operator
 typically has only one eigenstate associated with an eigenvalue of 1: this
 is the ground state or equilibrium state.
 All other eigenstates are associated with real eigenvalues that are less
 than one: upon iteration, the associated eigenstates must necessarily die
 away geometrically.
 This behaviour is physically appealing: it describes the approach to equilibriu
m of a system that may initially be far from equilibrium, and it provides
 a set of time scales at which that approach is made.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The transfer operator of the Bernoulli map is called the Bernoulli operator
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{B}$
\end_inset

 and is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[\mathcal{L}_{B}f\right](x)=g(x)=\frac{1}{2}\left(\; f\left(\frac{x}{2}\right)+f\left(\frac{1+x}{2}\right)\;\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 When 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is the space of polynomials, the eigenfunctions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L_{B}}$
\end_inset

 are the Bernoulli polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{n}(x)$
\end_inset

, and are associated with the eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{-n}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset LatexCommand cite
key "Gas92,Dri99,Ve-B04"

\end_inset

.
 The constant function 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{0}(x)=1$
\end_inset

 is associated with the eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

; it is the only non-decaying eigenfunction associated with the iteration
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{B}$
\end_inset

: the equilibrium state is a constant distribution.
 The spectrum of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{B}$
\end_inset

 is discrete.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If one considers a larger space of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

, then one finds that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{B}$
\end_inset

 has a larger set of eigenvalues.
 For example, if one considers the collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}^{\infty}(0,1)$
\end_inset

 of infinitely-differentiable functions on the 
\emph on
open
\emph default
 unit interval (
\emph on
i.e
\emph default
.
 not containing the endpoints), then the spectrum of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{B}$
\end_inset

 is continuous, and takes on all values in the unit disk 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\lambda\right|<1$
\end_inset

 of the complex plane.
 The eigenstates are given by the Hurwitz zeta function
\begin_inset LatexCommand cite
key "Ve-B04"

\end_inset

.
 The spectrum is degenerate, in that there are multiple eigenstates associated
 with each eigenvalue.
 Curiously, linear combinations of the Hurwitz zeta function may be taken,
 constructing the fractal Blancmange or Takagi curve.
 That is, for every eigenvalue on the complex unit disk, there is a correspondin
g fractal curve that is an eigenvector of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{B}$
\end_inset

, with that fractal having a dyadic self-symmetry.
 The Takagi curve is continuous but differentiable nowhere; however, it
 is bounded, and it is integrable.
 In this larger space, there is still only one unique eigenvector with eigenvalu
e one: this is still the constant function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is yet a larger space of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 that one may consider, and this is the space of functions that are continuous
 nowhere on the unit interval and are unbounded in magnitude, but are, in
 a certain sense, integrable.
 In classical analysis, such functions are outcasts, seemingly intractable
 and uncoercible.
 However, they may in fact be constructed in a very natural fashion: these
 are functions on the state space of a one-dimensional lattice model.
 They may be mapped to the unit interval with the dyadic mapping, and when
 mapped in this way, are plainly discontinuous and generally beastly.
 However, the lattice posses an alternate topology, which makes these functions
 not only manipulable but well-studied.
 Examples of functions on the lattice include the energy of the Ising model,
 or the Boltzmann probability distribution of the set of states of the Ising
 model.
 In the lattice model, the Bernoulli map corresponds to nothing more than
 the shift of the lattice by one: a translation of the lattice.
 The eigenvectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{B}$
\end_inset

 are simply functions whose magnitude changes geometrically as the lattice
 is shifted by one: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{B}$
\end_inset

is just the shift operator.
 Curiously, there is now a very large class of functions associated with
 the eigenvalue one: this is the class of translation-invariant functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The remainder of this paper is devoted to an exposition of the lattice-model
 construction of eigenstates of the transfer operator.
 An exploration is made not only of the Bernoulli map, which corresponds
 to a one-sided lattice, but also to the baker's map, which corresponds
 to a two-sided lattice.
 Since such continuous-nowhere functions seem outrageous, a motivation for
 this study is provided in the next section.
 It is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

multi-fractal measure
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, the derivative of the Minkowski question mark function, which is continuous
 nowhere, and unbounded, and yet is integrable.
 As multi-fractals occur naturally in physical systems, one cannot simply
 dismiss such crazy eigenvectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{B}$
\end_inset

 as unphysical: they are not only physical, but actually observed.
\end_layout

