\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The two-sided lattice is the lattice that stretches off to both the left
 and the right.
 The state of the two-sided lattice may be represented by two numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le x,y\le1$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 given by equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:dyadic map"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 likewise, but instead being a sum over the negative indexes, starting at
 
\begin_inset Formula $k=-1$
\end_inset

.
 The energy is a simple sum of the energy of the half-lattices to the left
 and to the right, plus an interaction term involving spins on both the
 left and right.
 The probability density is a product of the probability densities on the
 left and right, adjusted by the interaction between the left and right
 sides.
