\begin_layout Standard
The shift operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 can be understood to be an operator that pops a bit off the right-hand
 half lattice, and pushes it onto the left half-lattice.
 In the dyadic notation, it can be recognized as the so-called 
\emph on
Baker's map
\emph default
, a map from the unit square onto itself that cuts the square into two pieces,
 and stacks and squashes them.
 That is, given a pair of numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 in the unit square, one has 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\tau(x,y)=\left(\frac{x+\left\lfloor 2y\right\rfloor }{2}\,,\,2y-\left\lfloor 2y\right\rfloor \right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The Baker's map can be studied in its own right as a discrete-time dynamical
 system, in that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 can be taken to define the time evolution of a unit square over a single
 time-step.
 The time evolution is invertible, in that the inverse map 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is uniquely defined, being 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\tau^{-1}(x,y)=\left(2x-\left\lfloor 2x\right\rfloor \,,\,\frac{y+\left\lfloor 2x\right\rfloor }{2}\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The inverse map can be seen to be identical to the forward map with 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

