\begin_layout Subsubsection
Gibbs states and fractal self-similarity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The physics of the Kac model provides insight to why the question mark has
 flat spots at every rational, and why its derivative is non-vanishing on
 the irrationals: only the irrationals are mapped to strings that don't
 terminate.
 In physics, such states are called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Gibbs states
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: they are the states that are associated with a finite thermodynamic energy.
 From the above presentation, we can deduce that the Gibbs states are in
 some sense 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

dense
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the space of all configurations; conversely, so are the non-Gibbs states.
 A rigorous notion of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

dense
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, however, requires a topology; a topology for the lattice models is constructed
 in a later section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Gibbs states may also be used to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

explain
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the fractal self-similarity of the question mark function.
 Both the Ising and the Kac potentials are translationally invariant, in
 that the total energy does not change as the shift operator is applied
 to the lattice.
 The translation invariance is an explicit part of the construction: it
 is used in equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Classical Hamiltonian"

\end_inset

 to construct the total energy.
 In a certain sense, the Gibbs states are precisely those states that are
 translationally invariant.
 That is, if one chooses some Gibbs state, and then chops off the leading
 binary digit, one must necessarily have another Gibbs state.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At first blush, the matching of real numbers to lattice model configurations
 given by the dyadic map of equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:dyadic map"

\end_inset

 may seem arbitrary: one might imagine a large class of maps that could
 connect these spaces.
 The seeming fractal nature of the problem may be a trick of the mind, wrapped
 up in the mapping of equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:dyadic map"

\end_inset

 instead of being intrinsic to the physics of the configuration space.
 This concern raises two important questions: does there exist a non-fractal
 mapping from the space of configuration states to the real number line,
 and how should the concept of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fractal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 be expressed on spaces, such as the space of states, whose topology is
 not naturally that of the real number line?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A reasonable requirement on a map from the configuration space to the reals
 would be that it somehow preserves the translation invariance.
 Translation invariance is an important physical requirement for a lattice
 model, and one would like to have this requirement reflected in the mapping.
 That is, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\Omega\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is some map that assigns a real number to each point 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in\Omega$
\end_inset

, the set of all possible states, then one might require that there exists
 a non-trivial function 
\begin_inset Formula $g:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
(f\circ\tau)(\sigma)=(g\circ f)(\sigma)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

is the shift operator.
 This requirement that the mapping preserve translation invariance is simply
 a requirement that there exists a commuting diagram:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\begin{array}{ccc}
\Omega & {f\atop \longrightarrow} & \mathbb{R}\\
\tau\downarrow &  & \downarrow g\\
\Omega & {\longrightarrow\atop f} & \mathbb{R}\end{array}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 It should now be clear that the representation of translation invariance
 on the real number line is a requirement that the mapping have a fixed
 point at which it is self-similar: that is, one must have 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
(f\circ\tau^{n})(\sigma)=(g^{n}\circ f)(\sigma)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 for all positive integers 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Translation invariance implies iteration; it is well understood that, in
 general, the iteration of functions of the real number line results in
 fractals.
 The above result is general; it applies to all one-dimensional lattice
 models, and is not dependent one the form of the interaction, or even on
 the number of states at a given lattice location.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the two-state model, there is another symmetry that one might expect
 to preserve: this is the symmetry under the interchange of the two states.
 In the absence of a magnetic-field-type interaction (so 
\begin_inset Formula $M=0$
\end_inset

 in equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Ising potential"

\end_inset

), one might expect an absolute symmetry.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho:\Omega\to\Omega$
\end_inset

 be this reflection operator, the operator that, given a string of letters
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, exchanges letter 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 (or state -1) for the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 (or state +1), and 
\emph on
vice-versa
\emph default
.
 Corresponding to this, one expects a function 
\begin_inset Formula $r:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 that makes the following diagram commute: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\begin{array}{ccc}
\Omega & {f\atop \longrightarrow} & \mathbb{R}\\
\rho\downarrow &  & \downarrow r\\
\Omega & {\longrightarrow\atop f} & \mathbb{R}\end{array}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Clearly, one has 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho^{2}(\sigma)=\sigma$
\end_inset

 the identity function, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{2}(x)=x$
\end_inset

 is the identity as well.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given such a translation-invariant homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, that has functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 acting as representations of translation and reflection, one has in essence
 constructed everything that is needed to have a fractal with dyadic symmetry.
 That is, one need only to recognize that 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 generate the dyadic monoid of the modular group 
\begin_inset Formula $SL(2,\mathbb{Z})$
\end_inset

.
 The elements of this monoid are of the form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\gamma=g^{a}\circ r\circ g^{b}\circ r\circ g^{c}\circ\cdots\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c,\ldots$
\end_inset

 are non-negative integers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, we have demonstrated a corollary, of sorts: no matter what the form
 of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, if it preserves the translation invariance of the lattice, then the Minkowski
 question mark will inevitably appear in the theory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This construction holds for essentially all two-state lattice models.
 That is, let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be the translation-invariant homomorphism as above, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $h:\Omega\to X$
\end_inset

 be just about any function to some space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 which commutes with the reflection operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(h\circ f^{-1}):\mathbb{R}\to X$
\end_inset

 is necessarily a fractal, having elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 of the dyadic monoid giving the set of self-symmetries of the fractal.
 (The details on why anything having dyadic monoid symmetry is a fractal
 are voluminously and excruciatingly detailed in my other writings).
 In particular, the result here is independent of the details of the interaction
 between spins (barring the magnetic interaction, which can also be taken
 care of).
 We conclude: 
\series bold
\emph on
all such lattice models have a fractal self-symmetry
\series default
\emph default
.
