\begin_layout Subsubsection
Measure theory and sigma-algebras on a lattice 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the above discussion, it is clear that taking the 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to\infty$
\end_inset

 limit of a one-dimensional lattice model will require a way to promote
 the sums over configuration space into integrals.
 As pointed out in the introduction, this is not a trivial matter, because
 the cardinality 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{N}$
\end_inset

 of the configuration space changes from finite to uncountable in the limit.
 In particular, it is known from measure theory that it is impossible to
 define integration on a point set with the cardinality of the continuum.
 To properly define integration, one must define a topology and a sigma-algebra
 first.
 A general presentation of this idea is given here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The machinery of measure theory forces a radical shift in the language,
 notation and concepts used to discuss the problem.
 First of all, one can no longer employ the idea that the space consists
 of a set of points.
 There is a reason for this: not every subset of of an uncountably-infinite
 set is "measurable".
 In fact, almost all subsets of an uncountably-infinite set are not measurable.
 So the very first step of measure theory is to throw away almost all subsets
 of the total space.
 One keeps only the measurable sets.
 The collection of measurable sets is countable, and to each such set one
 assigns a (non-negative) size or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

measure
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 This collection forms a topology, in the sense that the intersection or
 union of any two measurable sets is also a measurable set, and has a size.
 Such a collection of sets, equipped with a size, and obeying an additional
 axiom, (that of sigma-additivity, to be defined), is called a sigma algebra.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this new language, the Hamiltonian takes on a new and very different
 appearance.
 It is no longer a function from points to the reals, but a function from
 elements of the sigma algebra to the reals.
 Intuitively, this "new" Hamilton can be visualized or intuited as the "average"
 of the old, classical Hamiltonian, the average taken over a certain subset
 of points.
 However, this intuition is dangerous, and can lead to errors: in particular,
 one has the chicken-and-egg problem of how to define the "average" of the
 old, classical Hamiltonian.
 The new Hamiltonian is different, and cannot be constructed from the old
 Hamiltonian.
 However, there is a way to prove that the new Hamiltonian is a faithful
 representation of the old one.
 If one has chosen one's sigma algebra wisely, then for every possible point
 in the old set, there is a sequence or filter or net of elements of the
 sigma algebra that contain the old point, and the measure of the elements
 in this sequence decreases to zero.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that the elements of this net are denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset

 for integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, and have a measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(a_{n})$
\end_inset

 The net is ordered so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(a_{n})<\mu(a_{k})$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $n>k$
\end_inset

.
 The "new" Hamiltonian is some function that assigns a real value to each
 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 We can then say that the new and the old Hamiltonians are equal or equivalent
 when, for the "classical" point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, the following are satisfied: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
p\in a_{n}\quad\forall n\in\mathbb{Z}^{+}\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\lim_{n\to\infty}\mu(a_{n})=0\]

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{H(a_{n})}{\mu(a_{n})}=E_{p}\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{p}$
\end_inset

 is the classical energy of the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 which the net is converging to.
 Again: to be clear: the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a possible configuration of the lattice model; each and every point
 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 corresponds to an infinite string in two letters, and 
\emph on
vice-versa
\emph default
, in one-to-one correspondence.
 If a net can be found for all points 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, and the above relationship holds for all points 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, and it holds for all possible nets to the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, then one may honestly and truthfully insists that the "new" and the "old"
 Hamiltonians "are the same".
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More generally, this sort of a measure-theoretic reformulation of integration
 over an uncountable set of points is referred to as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

second quantization
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in physics, and the integration is referred to as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

functional integration
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 A word of caution: standard treatments of second quantization in physics
 texts do not follow the above construction.
 This approach only becomes apparent in mathematical treatments of second
 quantization (need ref), where the aim is to construct a topological space
 over which integration can be performed.
 In the following, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

old
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Hamiltonian shall be called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

classical Hamiltonian
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, as it deals with points.
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

new
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Hamiltonian will be called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

quantum Hamiltonian
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, because the sigma algebra may be used to define functional integrals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The cylinder set topology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The natural topology for the configuration space of one-dimensional lattice
 models has a sub-base that consists of cylinder sets.
 It is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

natural
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the sense that there is a simple and natural action of the shift operator
 on the cylinder sets, and that there is a natural way to assign a size
 to the cylinder sets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The sub-base of a topology is a collection of sets such that any finite
 intersection or union of such sets belongs to the topology, and that furthermor
e, every set in the topology can be written as a finite intersection or
 union of sets in the sub-base.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A sigma algebra then consists of the topology, together with a function,
 the measure, that assigns a non-negative, real value to every element of
 the topology.
 The measure must satisfy a property called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sigma-additivity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: the measure of the union of a number of disjoint sets must equal the sum
 of the measures of each set.
 Notationally, sigma-additivity requires that:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mu\left(\bigcup_{i\in I}\, a_{i}\right)=\sum_{i\in I}\mu\left(a_{i}\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where each of the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

 are pairwise-disjoint from the other sets, and 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a (countable) collection of indexes of the sets being considered.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The cylinder sets may be defined as follows.
 Let the positions on the lattice be labeled by an integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 The elements of the sub-base of the sigma algebra can be completely enumerated
 by ordered pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $(n,s)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is a string in two letters of finite length 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, for integer 
\begin_inset Formula $k<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 The pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(n,s)$
\end_inset

 is to be visualized as the set of all states where the lattice values between
 location 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n+k-1$
\end_inset

 are equal to the string 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{(n,s)}$
\end_inset

 denote an element of this sub-base.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The sub-base of a topology is a collection of sets, which, by intersection
 and union, generate the rest of the topology.
 A brief review of intersection and union is in order.
 The intersection 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{(n,s)}\cap C_{(m,t)}$
\end_inset

 is the set of all configurations that match 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
AND
\emph default
 match 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 The union 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{(n,s)}\cup C_{(m,t)}$
\end_inset

 is as above, with 
\emph on
OR
\emph default
 taking the place of 
\emph on
AND
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let the two letters that occur in the string be 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 Then, for example, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
C_{(n,A)}\cap C_{(n,B)}=\varnothing\]

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \[
C_{(n,AAA)}\cap C_{(n,AAB)}=\varnothing\]

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \[
C_{(n,A)}\cup C_{(n,B)}=\Omega\]

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 representing the entire space.
 One noteworthy aspect of this topology is the somewhat intuitively "backwards"
 relation between the string labels and the sets, in that when two strings
 overlap, its is likely that the intersection of the corresponding sets
 will be empty, whereas when the strings don't overlap, the intersection
 will never be empty.
 Thus, for example, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
C_{(n,s)}\cap C_{(m,t)}\ne\varnothing\]

\end_inset

whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $m>n+\mbox{len}(s)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{len}(s)$
\end_inset

 is the length of the string.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Measures on cylinder sets 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The measure is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 that assigns to each element 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{(n,s)}$
\end_inset

 a real, non-negative value.
 It is convenient to normalize the measure such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(\varnothing)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(\Omega)=1$
\end_inset

.
 The requirement of sigma-additivity implies that all other values will
 be less than one.
 A measure will be said to be 
\emph on
translation invariant
\emph default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(C_{(n,s)})=\mu(C_{(m,s)})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

